                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d696">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/9531</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Under Secretary of
                        State</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-20">March 20,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>After the conclusion of the general conference with the Soviet Ambassador this
                        afternoon,<note n="23" xml:id="d696fn23">No record has been found in
                        Department files.</note> I asked the Ambassador to remain in order that I
                    might talk with him alone for a few minutes. The Ambassador asked if I had any
                    further information in confirmation of what I stated to him secretly in our last
                        interview,<note n="24" xml:id="d696fn24">See telegram No. 256, March 4, 7
                        p.m., to the Ambassador in the Soviet Union, <ref target="#pg_714">p.
                            714</ref>.</note> namely, that this Government believed that Germany was
                    planning to attack the Soviet Union. I said that I had additional information in
                    confirmation of that report.<note n="25" xml:id="d696fn25">On March 19, 1941,
                        the Greek Minister, Cimon Diamantopoulos, left a memorandum with Under
                        Secretary of State Welles wherein it was stated that the Greek Government
                        had received information that the Swedish Government had learned through its
                        Missions in Berlin, Bucharest, and Helsinki from German sources that there
                        were indications of serious discussions that “Germany could attack Russia.”
                        (740.0011 European War 1939/9288)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">umner</hi>] W[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >elles</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
